<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n40128d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n40" href="#n40128d">N40 (VI.B.28B)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n40all.htm#n40128d"> 128(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> paraclete </blockquote> <dd class="well"><mm class="note">Note: This word occurs 5 times in the New Testament, all in the writings of John. Four instances are in the Gospel and one in the First Epistle. In the Gospel the in the Epistle, 1 John 2:1. &ldquo;Paraclete&rdquo; is simply the Greek word transferred into English. The translation of the word in English Versions of the Bible is &ldquo;Comforter&rdquo; in the Gospel, and &ldquo;Advocate&rdquo; in the Epistle. The Greek word is <i>parakletos</i>, from the verb <i>parakaleo</i>. The word for &ldquo;Paraclete&rdquo; is passive in form, and etymologically signifies &ldquo;called to one&apos;s side.&rdquo; The active form of the word is <i>parakletor</i>, not found in the New Testament but found in Septuagint in Job 16:2 in the plural, and means &ldquo;comforters,&rdquo; in the saying of Job regarding the &ldquo;miserable comforters&rdquo; who came to him in his distress. </mm> </dd></dl>
